<h1 id="ii">II</h1>

<p>My parents couldnâ€™t be faulted for not being very particular about how I was going about my exams. They had grown up in refugee families in post-partition Punjab, a large part of their childhood having been spent in helping their uprooted families rebuild from scratch. In their generation, any educational degree - no matter how acquired - was valued. Whatâ€™s more, in their careers, whom you knew had mattered more than what you knew, a dynamic they themselves had suffered from.  Firm believers in good morals and the virtue of hard work, they had struggled to rise in their government jobs, while their colleagues worked their up doling out  â€˜special Mithaisâ€™ and â€˜Diwali giftsâ€™ to office superiors. It always surprised and confused me. â€œWhy donâ€™t we give gift sweets to your bosses as well?â€ Iâ€™d ask them, and theyâ€™d look at each other, in a strange, dazed sort of half amused, half melancholic expression, then look back at me, and say, â€œJust stay in <em>acchi sangati</em>, be good to one and everyone, and youâ€™d succeed.â€ That never answered my question, but I was clever, perceptive, and quick to interpret: If you invest in forming bonds at the top of the ladder early on, theyâ€™d pull you up later in life.</p>

<p><!--- Their experience had left a deep impression on me, with a vague sense that if you invest in forming bonds at the top of the ladder early on, they'd pull you up later in life.
 ---></p>

<p>Two years after that awkward parents-teacher meeting, I told my parents I wanted to go to St. Edmundâ€™s, the most prestigious all boys-convent school in the city. Quite how it had got that reputation I had no idea, but the richer kids in my neighbourhood - the ones who were driven around in chaffeured cars and lived in houses that were more glass than brick, and whoâ€™d never mix with us in the playground, all went to St. Edmundâ€™s.</p>

<p>There was, of course, the small matter of the admission. Elite schools rarely base their decisions on the merit or manners of the prospective student. Instead, they judge parents;  particularly, they look for wealth, class and influence. Our modest middle class family possessed neither. We were not rich. Neither could we afford donations. Nor did we have a circle of friends in high society whoâ€™d write me a reference or make a few phone calls. The only memory I had of my mother pulling a few strings was the time she knitted me a sweater.</p>

<p>Luckily, St. Edmundâ€™s also had one or two spots reserved for students with exceptional scholarship prospects, which helped the school put on a gloss of academic excellence in its prospectus. This â€œmeritocraticâ€ route involved taking an entrance exam, an exam which was to be broad, unpredictable and new. In other words, an exam where my old hacks woudnâ€™t work.</p>

<p>But by now my memory had improved, and my methods had evolved. I had figured a rhyming couplet at the start or the end usually sprinkles a touch of originality into an essay. I even came up my own poetry algorithm for generating such a verse. It went like this:</p>

<blockquote>
  <ul>
    <li>Think up a word resonating with the theme of the essay</li>
    <li>Make up a sentence ending with it</li>
    <li>Run from A to Z to find a rhyming word</li>
    <li>Make up a second related sentence ending with it</li>
    <li>If the couplet still seems out of sorts: loop</li>
  </ul>
</blockquote>

<p>In the exam, I was asked to write an essay on â€˜Spending New Yearâ€™s with Family,â€™ and my algorithm yielded:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p><em>When the earth completes one revolution around the Sun,</em><br />
  <em>Itâ€™s New Yearâ€™s day, and my family has a lot of fun!</em></p>
</blockquote>

<p>I got in. Maybe they saw an element of non-sequitur humour in it. Maybe they made allowances for the aesthetic judgements of a ten year old. But my algorithm for poetry worked. At St. Edmundâ€™s, I would continue to employee it to deadly effect in more terribly-judged poetry contests; meanwhile my parents would gloat around about the budding poet theyâ€™ve been bringing up.</p>

